Many people asked to replace x in |x| into the square.
Also, many people asked to replace x^n into the (bigger-square)^(small-square) telling the empty square symbolizes any element inside of the square, not just x. Actually, their logic is pretty good and realistic, so we implemented this logic.

content: First the bad: The worst thing I can say about this calculator is that it takes a little while to get used to the way it does things and persistence to discover how incredibly versatile it is. Now the good: Almost every facility you can think of from factorising quadratic expressions to solving pentics (?), from raising numbers to complex powers to graphs in both cartesian and polar coordinates. It can mix radians and degrees in the same calculation. It can calculate definite integrals. An astonishingly versatile app. Moreover it has several calculator work spaces and several graphic work spaces - you decide how many you want in both cases - so you can keep earlier work to refer to later. P.S. It can also add 2 and 3 and find 1000! - that's factorial 1000. ;)

content: As an engineer, I didn't need a calculator. I needed a tool that would let me solve complex problems on the go; review and share it in an easy to read, visual format; and save, review, and reuse my work. MathLab Graphing Calculator does all of that, with its graphical equation editing; user-defined functions and constants; history and workspaces; and seamless integration with Google Drive, DropBox, and other services. It's the closest thing I've found to Mathcad on Android.

This is the best graphing calculator on the market! They do it right. Continually adding new support for functions and multiple ways to display answers, this calculator also supports 3d graphing! Anything you could want from a graphing calculator, this app has it.

Works great and is even more intuitive than an actual graphing calculator in some instances. Great if your teacher will allow it, but note they often won't on tests. Still doesn't have to stop you from using it on homework or in the field.

replyContent:
Counting fractions, you see the result in both: fraction and decimal

To convert a Decimal to a Fraction:
1. Write down the decimal divided by 1, like this: decimal 1
2. Multiply both top and bottom by 10 for every number after the decimal point
3. Simplify (or reduce) the fraction

Lets economize the screen space by not showing the simplest things

content: How to do linear regretion for (3,4)(4,5)(6,7)(x,y)?
replyContent: If it does not fit on one line, use variables just like in your own example. A=[[...]], then use A on next line. That way you will not have to repeat it again and again. If you need column vector, don't forget to transpose it b^T. Vectors are row vectors by default.
